SIMPLE: patience
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Patience
<hw>Pa"tience</hw> <pr>(p⟦amac⟧"sh⟦eit⟧ns)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>patience</ets>, fr. L. <ets>patientia</ets>. See
<er>Patient</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or quality of being
patient; the power of suffering with fortitude; uncomplaining endurance
of evils or wrongs, as toil, pain, poverty, insult, oppression,
calamity, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Strengthened with all might, . . . unto all <qex>patience</qex>
and long-suffering.</q> <rj><qau>Col. i. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I must have <qex>patience</qex> to endure the load.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who hath learned lowliness⟦br⟧
From his Lord's cradle, <qex>patience</qex> from his cross.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act or power of calmly or contentedly waiting
for something due or hoped for; forbearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have <qex>patience</qex> with me, and I will pay thee all.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. xviii. 29.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Constancy in labor or application;
perseverance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He learned with <qex>patience</qex>, and with meekness taught.</q>
<rj><qau>Harte.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Sufferance; permission.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They stay upon your <qex>patience</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of dock (<spn>Rumex
Patientia</spn>), less common in America than in Europe; monk's
rhubarb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>Solitaire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Patience</er>, <er>Resignation</er>.</syn>
<usage> <xex>Patience</xex> implies the quietness or self-possession of
one's own spirit under sufferings, provocations, etc.;
<xex>resignation</xex> implies submission to the will of another. The
Stoic may have <xex>patience</xex>; the Christian should have both
<xex>patience</xex> and <xex>resignation</xex>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patient</ent>⟦br⟧
